recent:
  - date: 2026-05-11
    pr: 4
    branch: feature/mcp-absorb-rest
    title: "Path B v1.3.0 — finish MCP absorption (B.2 + B.3 + B.4)"
    state: MERGED
    merge_commit: 716dcab
    summary: |
      Completes Path B — `rforge_status` + `rforge_init` ported to `lib/`;
      `rforge-mcp` archive paperwork drafted in `docs/migration/`. After
      this lands, the plugin is fully self-sufficient — no MCP server
      required at runtime for any of the 7 implemented MCP tools.

      Consolidated 3 worktrees → 1 (B.2 + B.3 + B.4 in one atomic PR).

      Scope correction during execution: MCP's `status` tool was a thin
      .STATUS reader, NOT the 4-mode contract the SPEC implied. ported
      faithfully; 4-mode design descoped to v1.4.0 (backlog).

      Pre-merge review caught 6 concerns; all addressed in commit
      14c37de (rebased SHA) before merge:
        - error handling consistency in init_context
        - format_text test_status column
        - 3× type:ignore cleanup via `is not None` narrowing
        - frozen=True on InitResult, __all__ added, blocking_issues None semantics
        - datetime isoformat consistency
        - .STATUS regex parser format coupling documented

      Final state: 65/65 pytest, 23/23 test-all.sh.

      Post-merge cross-repo work pending: archive data-wise/rforge-mcp
      on GitHub (paperwork drafted in docs/migration/, executes manually).

  - date: 2026-05-10
    pr: 3
    branch: feature/mcp-absorb-discovery
    title: "feat: Path B Phase B.1 — port discovery + deps to lib/"
    state: MERGED
    merge_commit: 951e055
    summary: |
      First Path B port. Three of rforge-mcp's tools (rforge_detect,
      rforge_deps, rforge_impact) now live as pure-Python modules in
      lib/. Plugin commands invoke them directly via `python3 -m lib.X`.
      Non-breaking: existing rforge-mcp users keep all functionality.

      Includes pre-PR self-review refactor (commit 5d95c7a) addressing
      2 blockers caught in review:
        - lib/ made a real Python package (was sys.path hack risking
          name collision)
        - assert → walrus operator in parse_description (assert is
          strippable under python -O)

      Final state: 36/36 pytest, 23/23 test-all.sh, public API
      unchanged. Pre-merge ORCHESTRATE-*.md removal per CLAUDE.md
      merge-cleanup rule (commit e37a6a9).

      Lines: +2335/-194 across 21 files (lib/__init__.py, discovery.py
      361 lines, deps.py 481 lines, 3 test files, 5 doc pages,
      scripts/gen_lib_reference.py, command updates).

  - date: 2026-05-10
    pr: 1
    branch: feature/craft-parity-foundations
    title: "Craft parity foundations: marketplace, hooks, skills (v1.2.0)"
    state: MERGED
    merge_commit: 83a7d4d
    summary: |
      Phases 1+2 of craft-parity roadmap shipped. Added marketplace.json,
      config.json (4 stub options), pretooluse.py (4 R-aware rules,
      1 BLOCK + 3 WARN), description-sync skill (first validation skill),
      docs (hooks-and-skills, configuration, architecture Mermaid),
      tests/test-all.sh (20 checks). Self-review caught hook contract bug
      (env vars vs stdin) — fixed in b413ab3 before merge. Same bug
      flagged + fixed upstream in craft (PR #125, separate session).

  - date: 2026-05-10
    type: post-merge polish (5 commits on dev)
    summary: |
      Post-merge cleanup pass after PR #1 landed. Tightened version-sync,
      eliminated rename-debt + monorepo-extraction debris, decoupled MCP.

      8c94582  chore(.STATUS): clean up worktree entry post-merge
      c2369ae  docs: package.json bump 1.1.0→1.2.0 + 9-link sweep + README v1.2.0 narrative
      cdf9c2e  chore: monorepo URL leftovers + harden versions_match (4 sources, was 2)
      957158b  docs: complete rforge-orchestrator → rforge rename across user-facing docs
      <next>   chore: drop rforge-mcp peer dep + Path B migration SPEC

      Cross-repo follow-ups:
      - Data-Wise/homebrew-tap PR #103 MERGED — deprecate! rforge-orchestrator formula
      - Data-Wise/craft PR #125 OPEN (separate session) — fix pretooluse stdin contract
      - Data-Wise/craft Issue #126 OPEN — 3 doc files still showing env-var contract

      Verified: 20/20 tests, 0 broken internal links, all 4 version sources
      sync at 1.2.0, npm install no longer fails on rforge-mcp 404.

decisions:
  - date: 2026-05-10
    decision: "MCP is now optional (Path A → B)"
    rationale: |
      User goal: maintain only rforge (not also rforge-mcp). Half of MCP's
      13 tools were placeholders; user is single-client (Claude Code, no
      Desktop/Cursor); plugin commands are markdown prompts that work via
      Claude Code's built-in tools without an MCP server.
    path_a_shipped:
      commit: <next>
      changes:
        - "package.json: drop peerDependencies.rforge-mcp"
        - "README.md: reframe Part 1 (MCP install) as optional"
        - "tests/test-plugin-structure.sh: remove Test 8 (peer-dep assertion)"
        - "CHANGELOG.md: document the decoupling in v1.2.0 entry"
    path_b_spec:
      file: docs/specs/SPEC-mcp-absorb-2026-05-10.md
      summary: |
        Migration plan for absorbing rforge-mcp's 7 implemented tools into
        rforge's lib/. 4 phases. Drops 6 placeholder MCP tools entirely.
        Estimated 3-4 sessions, not urgent — A already unblocks npm install.

backlog:
  - title: "craft-parity Phase 3 — command namespacing (BREAKING, v2.0.0)"
    notes: "Biggest open item. Rename all 16 /rforge:* commands per craft's namespacing scheme, write migration tutorial, bump major. Start with /brainstorm to scope rename mechanics + user-migration ergonomics before writing code."
  - title: "craft-parity Phase 4 — discovery engine + agents (v2.1.0)"
    notes: "Depends on Phase 3 landing. Adds agent definitions that mirror craft's discovery engine."
  - title: "Path B v1.4.0 — restore 4-mode status contract (descoped from v1.3.0)"
    spec: docs/specs/SPEC-mcp-absorb-2026-05-10.md
    notes: "lib/status.py shipped as a thin faithful port in v1.3.0. The 4-mode contract (default/debug/optimize/release with R subprocess) was descoped pending real-user input on what depth is wanted. Open a new SPEC when there's demand."

